247. ma pendentem ferit, ‘she hits him when he’s down.' The expression is taken from the custom of tying a slave up to flog him. He is helpless to resist, and so the lover here. So Most. 1 167 uerberibus caedere multum pendens, Men. 951 ego te pendentem fodiam stimulis, διο. There are similar descriptions of the lady’s mercilessness, Truc. 50 ff. and 425 ff. ἰαωεῆδη, ⁴ forthwith.' But orat without a personal object is odd, and possibly iam amplius orat should be expunged as a gloss on pendentem jerit, and ni amplius etiam as another gloss. ibi pendentem ferit: non satis id est mali, (pps. ei for mali ?) quod ecbibit, quod comest, quod facit sumpti.

250. sumpti, gen. of sumptus, 4th decl. This is in the Comedians the normal genitive of the 4th declension. Other instances are peni, v. 254 (though this may be gen. srom the neuter form penum), gemiti, uicti, tumulti, quaesti, senati. Quintilian in the first cent. A. D. says that it is 'impossible to decide whether senatus or senati is the proper gen. of senatm. See Neue, Formenl. 1. p. 352 ff„ Roby, L. G. 399.
